## Using the KB

The knowledge base lives in `kb/`. Search it when the user asks about decisions, reasoning, design rationale, or project knowledge.

### Collection Routing

Collections are `kb/` subtrees with a local `COLLECTION.md`. Read the target collection's `COLLECTION.md` before writing or connecting artifacts there.

| Path | Role | Use when |
|---|---|---|
| `kb/notes/` | user theoretical register | Writing transferable claims, mechanisms, definitions, synthesis, and project-specific theory. |
| `kb/reference/` | user descriptive register | Describing the current system, architecture, interfaces, decisions, and operational surface. |
| `kb/instructions/` | user prescriptive register | Writing project-specific procedures, skills, operational rules, and how-to guidance. |
| `kb/sources/` | user source material | Storing external snapshots, ingests, and source reviews. |
| `kb/work/` | user workshop layer | Holding in-flight investigations, drafts, migration plans, and temporary work that should eventually close or promote durable artifacts. |
| `kb/commonplace/notes/` | shipped methodology library | Reading Commonplace theory and examples without mixing them into the user's own notes. |
| `kb/commonplace/reference/` | shipped Commonplace docs | Looking up Commonplace architecture, commands, type system, and ADRs. |
| `kb/commonplace/instructions/` | shipped Commonplace procedures | Reading framework procedures and promoted `cp-skill-*` skill bodies. |
| `kb/commonplace/` | namespace, not a collection | Locating shipped library collections; do not treat the namespace itself as governed content. |
| `kb/types/` | global type surface, not a collection | Looking up shared type specs used by both user and shipped collections. |

### Navigation

For the full model, read `kb/commonplace/reference/navigation.md`. In short: use `rg` for cheap lexical search, scan titles and descriptions in curated indexes and scoped `rg` listings before opening full files, and follow authored links when local context makes the relationship useful.

Entry points:

- `kb/reference/README.md` — current-state documentation for this system and links to its ADRs
- `kb/commonplace/reference/README.md` — shipped Commonplace documentation entry point

<!-- Add curated tag READMEs here as they emerge. When 5+ related notes accumulate under a tag, create `kb/notes/<tag>-README.md` (type `kb/types/tag-readme.md`): an orientation paragraph plus selective picks with context phrases. It may declare validator-enforced marks — `complete: true` (links every tagged note) or `covered_by: [children]` (every tagged note carries a listed child tag); see `kb/types/tag-readme.md`. -->

```bash
# Find notes by description
rg "^description:" kb/notes/ kb/reference/ kb/instructions/ kb/commonplace/notes/ kb/commonplace/reference/ kb/commonplace/instructions/ --glob "*.md"

# Find notes by type (types are path-valued)
rg "^type: kb/types/note.md" kb/notes/ kb/reference/ kb/instructions/ kb/commonplace/notes/ kb/commonplace/reference/ kb/commonplace/instructions/ --glob "*.md"

# Find notes by tag
rg "^tags:.*my-tag" kb/notes/ kb/reference/ kb/instructions/ kb/commonplace/notes/ kb/commonplace/reference/ kb/commonplace/instructions/ --glob "*.md"
```

### Skills

`commonplace-init` installs the `cp-skill-*` family (`cp-skill-write`, `cp-skill-validate`, `cp-skill-connect`, etc.) into `.claude/skills/` and `.agents/skills/`. The harness loads them automatically.

### Commands

The `llm-commonplace` package provides `commonplace-*` CLI commands for validation, snapshots, note operations, and the review system. For the full reference, read [kb/commonplace/reference/commands.md](./kb/commonplace/reference/commands.md).

